verbatim_name: PBDB explanation of how to enter taxonomic names and taxonomic modifiers: https://paleobiodb.org/public/tips/occurrence_tips.html    https://paleobiodb.doit.wisc.edu/public/tips/occurrence_tips.html

umber = subspecies, etc. that cannot be entered until PBDB structure changes.  To use "group" and "forma" or to use abbreviations will be decided for PBDB Taxonomy Team, so we will hold on formatting those entries for now
green = taxaonomic names that need to be entered into the PBDB
"verbatim_name" vs. "name" columns: extra spaces were removed when creating "name", so only need to look at "name" column
"name to use" can only be proper taxonomic names (of any level), see PBDB tip sheet for what is allowed. "Taxonomic comment" is just a text string and thus can be anything

For planktic forams, the way sinistral vs dextral is indicated is not standardized - sometimes is D and S, sometimes is sin and dex, sometimes its sinistral and dextral. We should decide on what we want to use

name: Pyrite
Comment: not a taxa; Going into Macrostrat, not PBDB
Notes (change to Internal only notes?): Summer 2020: deal with later; should go in as a taphonomony comment or sediment descriptor? LL: this is a sediment descriptor and I don't think it should go in the PBDB AF: the only place it might go is in as taphonomy, but then it'd get linked to every taxonomic occurence in the sample, right? That's not helpful. So delete, unless Joc that spurs some kind of thought. hmmm,  yes, I think by moving this to a taphonomy field, iit would be associated with the entire sample, rather than just the bfs... That's fine though, since it's relevant to the entire sample and not just the BFs. I think then it goes in taphonomy and/or sed descriptor. MAR '21: we have decided this should be a sed descriptor, will need to specify the name of the field in Baggage Stripper so that S & W-Y can map this correctly. Apr '21: AF and LL discussing with S, will update this row and Wai-Yin on what to do with this and other 'Sed Descriptor' entries.

name: Phytolith
Notes (change to Internal only notes?): Summer 2020: go in as "Plantae indet.", "phytolith" as a comment? Deal with later, ask Ellen and co LL: yes, ask Ellen's phytolith friend. JAS emailed Caroline Stromberg about this: "'Phytolith' is listed in a few of the taxa lists of various drilling expeditions, and I was wondering if the 'Poaceae indet.' would be the formal taxonomic name? Or do other non-grasses make phytoliths, and so we would need to coarsen up to a higher taxonomic group?"  from Caroline: "Poaceae indet.” would not be correct, since not all phytoliths are produced by grasses (although the likelihood is reasonably great if near a region with a lot of grasslands). "Plantae indet.” would be better. So, coarse!"  -- given this, put "phytolith" in quotes, rather than "Plantae indet."

name: Bortyostrobus auritus/australis

Winter 2021: From David Lazarus: Best call this 'Euchitonia elegans/furcata group’  for now. It is in NSB at the moment as a valid taxon [id 2004045].
